solutions.content:
***Question:***
To return the number of unique k-diff pairs in the array.
Input: nums = [3,1,4,1,5], k = 2
Answer: 2. Two pairs (1,3) and (3,5)

**Using HashMap:**
Just see for an element num, there exists num+k.
We essentially need to store count of number,to not mis-intrepet same number as its pair when k=0.

**TimeComplexity:** HashMap put and get operations are O(1) with assumption that key-value pairs are well distributed across the buckets. But in worst case, if we need to add multiple elements to one bucket so it can be O(n) .

**Space complexity:** In worst case all elements may be unique,so O(n).
```
class Solution {
    public int findPairs(int[] nums, int k) {
        //HashMap to store value-count
        Map<Integer, Integer> hashmap = new HashMap();

		int result = 0;
        /*
        for every number ,
        if number is seen for the first time ,then put count=1
        else ,increment the count
        */
        for(int num : nums)
            hashmap.computeIfAbsent(num, hashmap.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);
        //For all the elements in hashmap
        for(int i : hashmap.keySet()){
            /*
            As contistion is given i != j && nums[j]-nums[i]=k,
            This make sure that same element is not counted 
            */
			if(k==0 && hashmap.get(i) > 1) result++;
            else if (hashmap.containsKey(i + k)) result++;
		}
        return result;
    }
}
```

**Using Binary-Search:**

Instead of using in-built methods of arrays.binarysearch(array,start,end,key), I used a utility function .

1.To apply binary search we need to sort array. 
2.After sorting we need to search for element "num" ,if there exists another element "num+k".

Improvement 1:
As we need unique pair,we dont search if current element is same as before.
Improvement 2:
As we sorted array in ascending order, we just need to start our binary search from current_index+1.So searching space considerly reduces.
As we are searching from index+1,this also make sure we are not considering same element when k=0.

**Time complexity :** O(n log(n)) for sorting, and for searching in worst case O(log(n)) .As we are doing search operation for n elements, O(n log(n)). Resultant time complexity will be O(n log(n)).

**Space complexity:**
O(1)[If not considering input array],beacuse we are using fixed number of variables.

