This was actually asked to me in an interview in a top product based company as an internal candidate.

1. This is an O(n) solution converted to C#, shared by others in Java.
Logic is very simple:
Build a dictionary (or map) with unique numbers in the array and store their count.
Eg. for the  input: `nums = [3,1,4,1,5] and k = 2`
3-1, there is only one 3
1-2, there are two 1s
4-1, there is only one 4
5-1, there is only one 5

	Next loop through each key-value pair in this map and see if there exists a key with current key + k (equivalent to Math.Abs(current key - target key) == k)

	Also, there is an edge case, for k==0. If k in the input was 0, then just check if the there were duplicate keys in the dictionary/map. This can be done just by checking the count of current key > 1. In above example, if k was 0, then - whenever we are at the number 1 we can see that there were two occurence of 1 in the array and thus we have a pair.

```
public int FindPairsWithDictionary(int[] nums, int k) {
        var pairsCount = 0 ;
        var map = new Dictionary<int, int>();
        foreach(var num in nums)
        {
            if (!map.ContainsKey(num))
            {
                map.Add(num, 0);
            }
            map[num]++;
        }

        foreach(var pair in map)
        {
            if (k > 0 && map.ContainsKey(pair.Key + k)) {
                pairsCount ++;
            }
            // special case
            if (k == 0 && pair.Value > 1)
            {
                pairsCount ++;
            }
        }

        return pairsCount;
    }

```

2. This is also a C# version for code shared by other people in the discussion. This one looks very simple, but has the overhead of sorting the array, going over the array multiple times. So, the time complexity is really high.
```
public int FindPairsWithSorting(int[] nums, int k) {
        var count = 0;
        var n = nums.Length;
        var result = new HashSet<int>();
        Array.Sort(nums);
        for (int i=0; i<n-1; i++) {
            var firstNumber = nums[i];
            for (int j=i+1; j<n; j++) 
            {
                if (nums[j] - firstNumber >  k) {
                    break;
                }

                if (nums[j] - firstNumber == k)
                {
                    if (!result.Contains(firstNumber) || !result.Contains(nums[j])) {
                        count++;
                    }
                    result.Add(firstNumber);
                    result.Add(nums[j]);                    
                }
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
```

