solutions.content:
The problem states that
```
A k-diff pair is an integer pair (nums[i], nums[j]), where the following are true:
- 0 <= i, j < nums.length
- i != j
- a <= b
- b - a == k
```
So either `(nums[i],nums[j])` or `(nums[j],nums[i])` is a sufficient k-diff pair. That means, the order of elements doesn't matter -> sort the array and use binary search.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int findPairs(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        int prev = INT_MIN, ret = 0, n = nums.size();
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            auto &v = nums[i];
            if (v != prev) {
                if (binary_search(nums.begin()+i+1,nums.end(),v+k)) {
                    ret++;
                }
                prev = v;
            }
        }
        return ret;
    }
};
```

